==Dutch==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|odt|nl}} {{term/t|odt|*hervist}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|nl}} {{term/t|gem-pro|*harbistaz}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|nl}} {{term/t|ine-pro|*kerp-}}, {{term/t|ine-pro|*skerp-}}. Related to High German {{term|Herbst|lang=de}}, Low German {{term|harvst|lang=nds}}, West Frisian {{term|hjerst|lang=fy}}, English {{term|harvest|lang=en}}, also Latin {{term|carpere||to [[pick]], to [[pluck]]|lang=la}}, Greek {{term|καρπός|tr=karpos||fruit, harvest|lang=grc}}. The original meaning is ''harvest time'', as is seen in {{term|herfstmaand|lang=nl}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/ɦɛr(ə)fst/|lang=nl}}
* {{audio|nl-herfst.ogg|Audio (Netherlands)|lang=nl}}

===Noun===
{{nl-noun|m|-|-}}

# [[autumn]], [[fall]]

====Usage notes====
The made-up compound noun {{term||herfstschrik|fear of Autumn}} ({{IPA|/hɛrfstsxrɪk/|lang=nl}}) is used to demonstrate the number of consonants that can be strung together in Dutch. It is not particularly difficult for a speaker of Dutch to pronounce all consonants, but in practice a few of these will be dropped to something like {{IPA|/hɛrfsxrɪk/|lang=nl}}.

